.\" diskcleanup.py - Disk Cleanup Utility man page
.\" Section 5: File Formats and Configuration
.\"
.TH DISKCLEANUP.PY 5 "April 18, 2026" "3.0.0" "Disk Cleanup Utility"
.\"
.\" ──────────────────────────────────────────────
.SH NAME
diskcleanup.py \- comprehensive disk cleanup utility with intelligent
file management, health monitoring, and daemon mode
.\"
.\" ──────────────────────────────────────────────
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B diskcleanup.py
.RB [ \-\-dry\-run ]
.RB [ \-\-config
.IR path ]
.RB [ \-\-verbose | \-v ]
.br
.B diskcleanup.py
.B \-\-daemon
.RB [ \-\-interval
.IR seconds ]
.RB [ \-\-config
.IR path ]
.br
.B diskcleanup.py
.RB [ \-\-report ]
.RB [ \-\-last
.IR N ]
.br
.B diskcleanup.py
.RB [ \-\-report\-csv ]
.RB [ \-\-last
.IR N ]
.br
.B diskcleanup.py
.RB [ \-\-version | \-V ]
.br
.B diskcleanup.py
.RB [ \-\-version\-dialog ]
.\"
.\" ──────────────────────────────────────────────
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B diskcleanup.py
is a comprehensive disk cleanup solution for Linux systems.
It reads a YAML configuration file and performs intelligent file management
including directory cleanup, log file truncation, ABRT crash dump management,
systemd journal log vacuuming, audit log cleanup, and service restart detection.
.PP
The utility can run as a one\-shot command, as a daemon with a built\-in
sleep loop, or on a schedule via cron or systemd timers.
.PP
Key capabilities include:
.RS 4
.IP \(bu 2
Cleanup directories by file age and extension, with regex pattern matching.
.IP \(bu 2
Recursive or top\-level\-only directory scanning, configurable globally and per directory.
.IP \(bu 2
Exclude patterns to protect specific files from cleanup (global and per\-directory).
.IP \(bu 2
Compressed file age detection \(em peeks inside .gz and .tar.gz headers to determine true age.
.IP \(bu 2
Monitor and truncate individual log files once they exceed a configured size.
.IP \(bu 2
Manage ABRT crash dumps by age and total directory size.
.IP \(bu 2
Vacuum systemd journal logs by size and age via journalctl.
.IP \(bu 2
Clean audit logs when disk usage exceeds a threshold percentage.
.IP \(bu 2
Detect and restart services holding deleted file handles.
.IP \(bu 2
Daemon mode with configurable interval, PID file, and graceful signal handling.
.IP \(bu 2
Dry\-run mode to preview potential savings without modifying anything.
.IP \(bu 2
System health monitoring with before/after comparison.
.IP \(bu 2
Run history tracking with trending reports and CSV export.
.IP \(bu 2
Protected path enforcement \(em refuses to operate on critical system directories.
.IP \(bu 2
Rich console output with progress tracking and detailed logging.
.RE
.\"
.\" ──────────────────────────────────────────────
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-\-dry\-run
Show what would be cleaned without actually removing or truncating any files.
Displays estimated space savings.
.TP
.BR \-\-config " " \fIpath\fR
Path to a YAML configuration file.
If not specified, the script searches for
.I diskcleanup.yaml
in the same directory as the script.
.TP
.BR \-\-verbose ", " \-v
Increase logging verbosity. Use
.B \-v
for verbose or
.B \-vv
for debug\-level output.
.TP
.BR \-\-daemon
Run as a daemon, performing cleanup on a recurring interval.
The process stays resident and re\-reads the YAML configuration each cycle.
See
.B DAEMON MODE
below.
.TP
.BR \-\-interval " " \fIseconds\fR
Override the daemon sleep interval in seconds.
Takes precedence over the YAML
.B daemon.interval
setting.
Only meaningful with
.BR \-\-daemon .
.TP
.BR \-\-report
Display a trending report from run history and exit.
.TP
.BR \-\-report\-csv
Export run history as CSV to stdout and exit.
.TP
.BR \-\-last " " \fIN\fR
Number of recent runs to include in the report. Default is 20.
.TP
.BR \-\-version ", " \-V
Print version information to the console and exit.
.TP
.BR \-\-version\-dialog
Show version information in a GUI dialog box (requires tkinter).
.\"
.\" ──────────────────────────────────────────────
.SH REQUIREMENTS
.IP \(bu 2
Python 3.6 or later
.IP \(bu 2
PyYAML, rich, arrow (install via
.BR "pip3 install \-r requirements.txt" )
.IP \(bu 2
Root privileges for system cleanup operations
.IP \(bu 2
Linux system with
.I /proc
filesystem
.\"
.\" ──────────────────────────────────────────────
.SH INSTALLATION
Place the script and its supporting files in a directory such as
.IR /opt/scripts/diskcleanup .
.PP
Install required Python modules:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
pip3 install \-r requirements.txt
.fi
.RE
.PP
To run the script hourly via cron, create
.IR /etc/cron.d/diskcleanup :
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
00 * * * * root /opt/scripts/diskcleanup/diskcleanup.py
.fi
.RE
.PP
Alternatively, use the provided systemd units (see
.BR "SYSTEMD INTEGRATION" ).
.\"
.\" ──────────────────────────────────────────────
.SH CONFIGURATION FILE
The script reads a YAML configuration file
.RI ( diskcleanup.yaml
by default) containing the following top\-level sections:
.BR main ,
.BR files ,
.BR directories ,
.BR journald ,
and optionally
.BR daemon .
.\"
.\" ──────────────────────────────────────────────
.SS Main Section
Global settings that control overall script behavior.
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
main:
  cleanup: true
  abrt_maxage: 30
  abrt_maxsize: 50 MB
  abrt_directory: /var/log/crash/abrt
  max_filesize: "2 GiB"
  max_fileage: 30
  check_services: []
  file_extensions:
    \- "tar.gz"
    \- ".gz"
    \- '.*\-\\d{8}'
  exclude_patterns:
    \- '\\.keep'
    \- 'compliance'
  directories_to_check:
    \- "/var/log"
  recursive: false
  audit_percent: 50
  compressed_age_detection: true
  log_file: diskcleanup.log
  history_file: diskcleanup_history.jsonl
.fi
.RE
.PP
.TS
allbox;
lb lb lb
l l l.
Parameter	Value	Description
cleanup	true | false	Enable or disable cleanup operations
max_filesize	size (KiB, MiB, GiB, TiB)	T{
Global maximum file size before truncation.
Must include a space between value and unit (e.g., "2 GiB").
T}
max_fileage	integer (days)	T{
Global maximum file age in days.
Files older than this are eligible for deletion.
T}
file_extensions	list of strings	T{
File extensions to target during directory cleanup.
Supports regex patterns (e.g., '.*\-\\d{8}').
T}
exclude_patterns	list of strings	T{
Regex patterns for files to exclude from cleanup.
Matched against both full path and filename.
T}
directories_to_check	list of paths	T{
Directories to scan during basic directory cleanup.
T}
recursive	true | false	T{
Enable recursive scanning for directories_to_check.
Defaults to false.
T}
compressed_age_detection	true | false	T{
Peek inside .gz and .tar.gz headers to determine true file age.
Defaults to true. Disable to use only filesystem mtime.
T}
abrt_maxage	integer (days)	Maximum age of ABRT crash dump directories before deletion
abrt_maxsize	size (MB or GB)	T{
Purge oldest ABRT directories when total size exceeds this value.
T}
abrt_directory	path	Directory containing ABRT crash dump files
audit_percent	0\-100	T{
Disk usage percentage threshold for audit log cleanup.
When exceeded, audit files are deleted until usage drops below this value.
T}
check_services	list of strings	T{
Service names to check for deleted file handles.
Services holding deleted files are restarted automatically.
T}
log_file	path or filename	T{
Log file location. If a bare filename is given, it is written
to the script directory. An absolute path may also be used.
T}
history_file	path or filename	T{
Run history file location. Defaults to diskcleanup_history.jsonl
in the script directory.
T}
.TE
.\"
.\" ──────────────────────────────────────────────
.SS Files Section
Lists individual files to monitor for size.
When a file exceeds its configured maximum size, it is truncated to 0 bytes.
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
files:
  "/var/log/mysqld.log": "5 MiB"
  "/var/log/mysql/mysql\-slow.log": {}
  "/var/log/logstash/logstash\-plain.log": {}
  "/var/log/kibana/kibana.log": {}
.fi
.RE
.PP
Each entry maps a file path to a size limit.
Use an explicit size string (e.g., "5 MiB") to override the global
.B max_filesize
for that file, or use
.B {}
to inherit the global default.
.\"
.\" ──────────────────────────────────────────────
.SS Directories Section
Defines per\-directory cleanup rules using regex file patterns.
Each directory can override the global
.B max_fileage
and specify its own file matching pattern.
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
directories:
  "/var/log/haproxy":
    max_fileage: 10
    file_pattern: "haproxy\-.*"
  "/var/log/kibana\-1":
    max_fileage: 3
    file_pattern: "kibana\-.*"
    exclude_pattern: "kibana\-recent"
    recursive: true
.fi
.RE
.PP
.TS
allbox;
lb lb lb
l l l.
Parameter	Value	Description
max_fileage	integer (days)	T{
Override the global max_fileage for this directory.
If omitted, the global default is used.
T}
file_pattern	regex string	T{
Regex pattern to match filenames.
Only matching files are eligible for deletion.
T}
exclude_pattern	string or list	T{
Additional exclude patterns specific to this directory.
Merged with global exclude_patterns.
T}
recursive	true | false	T{
Whether to recurse into subdirectories.
Defaults to true for pattern directories.
T}
.TE
.PP
To match multiple file patterns within a single directory, use the regex
alternation operator:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
file_pattern: "[logfile1_.*|filebeat\-.*]"
.fi
.RE
.\"
.\" ──────────────────────────────────────────────
.SS Journald Section
Controls systemd journal log vacuuming.
Requires a system running systemd; gracefully skipped on non\-systemd hosts.
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
journald:
  cleanup: true
  max_size: "500 MB"
  max_age: "30d"
.fi
.RE
.PP
.TS
allbox;
lb lb lb
l l l.
Parameter	Value	Description
cleanup	true | false	Enable or disable journald vacuuming
max_size	size string	T{
Maximum journal size. Maps to journalctl \-\-vacuum\-size.
T}
max_age	duration string	T{
Maximum journal age (e.g., "30d", "2weeks"). Maps to journalctl \-\-vacuum\-time.
T}
.TE
.\"
.\" ──────────────────────────────────────────────
.SS Daemon Section
Optional settings for daemon mode. Only used when
.B \-\-daemon
is passed.
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
daemon:
  interval: 3600
  pid_file: /var/run/diskcleanup.pid
  max_consecutive_errors: 5
.fi
.RE
.PP
.TS
allbox;
lb lb lb
l l l.
Parameter	Value	Description
interval	integer (seconds)	T{
Sleep interval between cleanup cycles. Default: 3600.
Overridden by the \-\-interval CLI flag.
T}
pid_file	path	T{
PID file path. Used to prevent duplicate daemon instances.
Default: /var/run/diskcleanup.pid.
T}
max_consecutive_errors	integer	T{
Exit the daemon after this many consecutive failures.
Default: 5.
T}
.TE
.\"
.\" ──────────────────────────────────────────────
.SH DAEMON MODE
When started with
.BR \-\-daemon ,
the script runs in a continuous loop:
.PP
.RS 4
.IP 1. 3
Write a PID file (exits if another instance is already running).
.IP 2. 3
Perform a full cleanup pass.
.IP 3. 3
Sleep for the configured interval.
.IP 4. 3
Re\-read the YAML configuration and repeat.
.RE
.PP
.B Signal handling:
.RS 4
.IP \(bu 2
.B SIGTERM / SIGINT
\(em graceful shutdown. The current sleep is interrupted and the daemon exits cleanly.
.IP \(bu 2
.B SIGHUP
\(em interrupts the sleep and triggers an immediate next cycle.
Useful for config reload (the config is re\-read every cycle anyway).
.RE
.PP
The PID file is removed on shutdown. If a stale PID file is found from a
crashed instance, the daemon detects the dead process and overwrites it.
.\"
.\" ──────────────────────────────────────────────
.SH PROTECTED PATHS
The script maintains a hardcoded set of protected system paths that can never
be targeted for cleanup, including
.IR / ,
.IR /etc ,
.IR /usr ,
.IR /home ,
.IR /boot ,
and others.
.PP
Additionally, any path shallower than depth 2 (e.g.,
.IR /var )
is rejected.
Paths that are parents of protected directories are also blocked.
.PP
Protection is enforced at two levels:
.RS 4
.IP \(bu 2
.B Configuration validation
\(em rejects protected paths at startup before any cleanup runs.
.IP \(bu 2
.B Runtime checks
\(em every cleanup function calls
.B validate_path_safety()
before performing any destructive operation.
.RE
.\"
.\" ──────────────────────────────────────────────
.SH COMPRESSED FILE AGE DETECTION
When
.B compressed_age_detection
is enabled (the default), the script peeks inside compressed files to
determine their true age:
.RS 4
.IP \(bu 2
.B .tar.gz / .tgz
\(em reads the mtime of the first tar archive member.
.IP \(bu 2
.B .gz
\(em reads the 4\-byte timestamp from the gzip header (bytes 4\-7).
.RE
.PP
The older of the filesystem mtime and the internal timestamp is used.
This prevents recently\-rotated compressed logs from being skipped when
the filesystem mtime reflects the rotation time rather than the log content age.
.PP
If the filesystem mtime already qualifies a file for cleanup, the archive
header peek is skipped for performance.
.\"
.\" ──────────────────────────────────────────────
.SH SYSTEMD INTEGRATION
Three systemd unit files are provided in
.IR contrib/systemd/ :
.TP
.B diskcleanup\-daemon.service
Runs diskcleanup.py in daemon mode with a built\-in sleep loop.
The script handles its own scheduling.
Supports
.B systemctl reload
to send SIGHUP and trigger an immediate cycle.
.TP
.B diskcleanup.service
One\-shot unit that runs a single cleanup pass and exits.
Pair with the timer below for systemd\-managed scheduling.
.TP
.B diskcleanup.timer
Triggers
.B diskcleanup.service
every hour with a randomized 5\-minute delay.
Persistent across reboots (catches up on missed runs).
.PP
To install the timer\-based approach:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
cp contrib/systemd/diskcleanup.service /etc/systemd/system/
cp contrib/systemd/diskcleanup.timer /etc/systemd/system/
systemctl daemon\-reload
systemctl enable \-\-now diskcleanup.timer
.fi
.RE
.PP
To install the daemon approach:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
cp contrib/systemd/diskcleanup\-daemon.service /etc/systemd/system/
systemctl daemon\-reload
systemctl enable \-\-now diskcleanup\-daemon.service
.fi
.RE
.\"
.\" ──────────────────────────────────────────────
.SH EXAMPLES
Run a dry\-run to preview what would be cleaned:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
diskcleanup.py \-\-dry\-run
.fi
.RE
.PP
Run cleanup with a custom configuration file:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
diskcleanup.py \-\-config /etc/diskcleanup/production.yaml
.fi
.RE
.PP
Run with verbose logging:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
diskcleanup.py \-\-verbose
.fi
.RE
.PP
Start as a daemon with a 30\-minute interval:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
diskcleanup.py \-\-daemon \-\-interval 1800
.fi
.RE
.PP
Show a trending report of the last 50 runs:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
diskcleanup.py \-\-report \-\-last 50
.fi
.RE
.PP
Export run history as CSV:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
diskcleanup.py \-\-report\-csv > cleanup_history.csv
.fi
.RE
.\"
.\" ──────────────────────────────────────────────
.SH FILES
.TP
.I diskcleanup.yaml
Default YAML configuration file (searched in the script directory).
.TP
.I diskcleanup.log
Default log file (written to the script directory unless overridden).
.TP
.I diskcleanup_history.jsonl
Run history file in JSON Lines format, used for trending reports.
.TP
.I requirements.txt
Python package dependencies.
.TP
.I diskcleanup/
Python package containing the modular components:
.BR config.py ,
.BR core.py ,
.BR health.py ,
.BR history.py ,
.BR logging.py .
.TP
.I contrib/systemd/
Systemd service and timer unit files.
.\"
.\" ──────────────────────────────────────────────
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Successful execution.
.TP
.B 1
Configuration error, missing configuration file, or daemon PID conflict.
